</div>
</p>
<p>That's called a tag, and you can put many as you want, separating each by a space.
At first, adding a tag does nothing except for the magic <code>@javascript</code> that changes
to use a JavaScript driver.</p>
<h2 id="running-things-before-a-tagged-scenario">Running things Before a Tagged Scenario <a class="headerlink" href="fixtures-tags#running-things-before-a-tagged-scenario" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>But in <code>FeatureContext</code> you can add an <code>@BeforeScenario</code> method that's <em>only</em> executed
when a scenario has a certain tag. Make a new <code>public function loadFixtures()</code>. Inside,
just to see if it's working, put <code>var_dump('GO!');</code>. Above, put the normal <code>@BeforeScenario</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="f1c37ba761">
